76561198166230474,Recommended,434570,27540684,"Posted: 25 November, 2016",all,Max Is Back,"Blood and Baconis a first-person shooter that pits you (and, optionally, up to 5 others in co-op mode) against hordes of deadly steroid-infused pigs. Some are small, some are big, some are HUGE, some are metal(?), some have apparently misplaced their skin and are entirely skeletal - but there are two things that they all have in common:1. They pose a severe risk to human life, especially yours.2. They must be humanely destroyed by a qualified veterinarian to avert a major public health hazard.The bad news is that they presumably killed all the qualified veterinarians so you'll have to do the job yourself. The good news is that you have a far more appropriate set of tools than the average vet - these include pistols, shotguns, machine guns, grenades and more.The basic format of the game is a round-based FPS where each round is represented by a new day. A round can consist of anywhere between a few and a fewhundredangry hogs. Each day you're given instructions by the Farmer, who needs your help to stem the tide of porcine peril because, for some inexplicable reason, one of his legs is missing and he's pinned to the wall of his barn with a pitchfork. The Farmer's musings are often hilarious and his voice-acting is great, but each day's task needs little explanation: kill the pigs -allthe pigs!There's only one map (the farm itself) and it's not very big. But there are various tools scattered about the environment to assist you in your task - an electric fence that will quickly turn any nearby pigs into pork scratchings, a meat grinder that (somehow) turns pig carcasses into useful pickups (ammo, grenades, power-ups) and water fountains from which you can replenish your health. Your arsenal of weapons and the tools around the farm are unlocked as the days go by but it won't take long to unlock everything you need for some serious pig-slaughtering mayhem. There are also plenty of secrets and easter eggs to be found all around the game.Every 10th day you'll encounter a mini-boss and every 20th day you'll encounter amassiveboss, so large that its final destruction produces an eruption of pig gibs that turns the entire sky red with blood. It's hard to describe just how satisfying this is but perhaps a quick screen-shot will help:http://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=806168815Not quite enough blood with your bacon? Well hold on there partner, we're just getting started:http://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=806169966Still not enough blood for you? Then you should probably seek professional psychiatric help. Moving on, there are also periodic ""revenge days"" where every weapon is loaded with explosive ammunition; let's just say things get messy.Originally an XBox Live Arcade title, it has now made the glorious transition to Steam where it has rapidly grown bigger, better and brasher than it ever was on the humble XBox 360. Developer ""Big Corporation"" is very active in the community, respects community feedback, implements good suggestions in a timely fashion, makes regular updates to the game and is all in all a great guy. Big Corporation genuinely loves the game and is constantly improving it, something I respect and admire in a developer.It's a simple but satisfying game and notably offers exceptional value for money - $0.99 (or your regional equivalent) at full price and you'll often find it on sale for 10% or even 20% off, so it could be yours from the spoils of a quick rummage down the back of the sofa for loose change. Needless to say, it's hardly going to compete with your triple-A FPS games but rest assured you get a whole lot of game (and a whole lot of fun) for the extremely modest price of admission.This is my nomination for the 2016 Steam Awards' ""Best Use of a Farm Animal"" category because what better use can there possibly be than turning it into an excessively bloody mess with an arsenal of lethal weaponry? It's a serious question, feel free to answer in the comments!So to wrap things up, pros and cons? Honestly, at this point you don't need a list of pros and cons since you should have stopped reading by now and bought it already - did I mention it costs less than a dollar?"
